'''2U, Inc.''' (formerly 2tor Inc.) is an [[educational technology]] company that partners with leading nonprofit colleges and universities to offer online degree programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/news/2012/04/18/2tor-gets-10m-credit-line.html |title=2tor gets $10M credit line - Washington Business Journal |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=2012-04-18 |accessdate=2012-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Alyson Shontell, provided by |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/04/18/businessinsidereducation-startups-a.DTL |title=There Are A Million Education Startups And No One To Acquire Them |publisher=Sfgate.com |date=2012-04-18 |accessdate=2012-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Heather R. Huhman |url=http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-04-11/tech/31323390_1_higher-education-internet-online-masters |title=The Future Of Education: How 2tor Is Helping America's Great Universities Go Online - Business Insider |publisher=Articles.businessinsider.com |date=2012-04-11 |accessdate=2012-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bolshaw |first=Liz |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/1e684bc2-71d0-11e1-8497-00144feab49a.html?ftcamp=published_links/rss/business-education/feed//product#axzz1tnOlwP7h |title=Out of sight but not out of mind in the virtual world |publisher=FT.com |date=2012-04-16 |accessdate=2012-05-03}}</ref> The company supplies its partner universities with a cloud-based [[Software as a service|software-as-a-service]] platform coupled with a suite of technology-enabled services, including coursework design, infrastructural support and capital to deliver instruction to students. 2U was founded in 2008 by [[John Katzman]] (founder of [[The Princeton Review]]). Co-founders include Chip Paucek (former CEO of [[Hooked on Phonics]]) and Jeremy Johnson; Paucek remains with the company as CEO.

In May 2012, [[Forbes]] named 2U as one of the "10 Start-Ups Changing the World.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pozin|first1=Ilya|title=10 Startups Changing the World And What We Can Learn From Them|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ilyapozin/2012/05/09/10-startups-changing-the-world-and-what-we-can-learn-from-them/|publisher=Forbes.com}}</ref>" In 2014, [[Inc. Magazine]] named 2U one of "10 Tech Companies Helping Humanity.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kerpen|first1=Dave|title=10 Tech Companies Helping Humanity|url=http://www.inc.com/dave-kerpen/10-tech-companies-impacting-humanity.html|publisher=Inc.com}}</ref>"

The company went public on March 28, 2014, and raised $119 million by offering 9.2 million shares at $13 per share.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Flook|first1=Bill|title=2U goes public, rings opening bell on NASDAQ|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2014/03/28/2u-goes-public.html|publisher=Baltimore Business Journal}}</ref> 2U is traded on NASDAQ under the ticker symbol TWOU.

Prior to its IPO, the company was venture-backed and raised $96 million. Investors included [[Bessemer Venture Partners]], [[Highland Capital Partners]], [[Redpoint Ventures]], Novak Biddle Venture Partners, [[City Light Capital]], SVB Capital and WestRiver Capital.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://betabeat.com/2012/04/02/2tor-closes-series-d/ | work=Betabeat | title=Online Higher Education Gets a Raise as 2tor Secures $26 M. in Series D Funding Round | year=2012}}</ref> In September 2017, It was reported that, Rani Hammond joined 2U as Chief People Officer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/brief-rani-hammond-to-join-2u-as-chief-p/brief-rani-hammond-to-join-2u-as-chief-people-officer-idUSASB0BJBA|title=BRIEF-Rani Hammond to join 2U as chief people officer|date=2017-09-13|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-10-13}}</ref>

As per September 2018, the net worth of the company raised to $4.7 Billion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/antoinegara/2018/09/25/mbas-in-pjs-inside-2u-the-47-billion-startup-that-brings-top-schools-to-your-laptop/|title=Ivory Tower In The Cloud: Inside 2U, The $4.7 Billion Startup That Brings Top Schools To Your Laptop|last=Gara|first=Antoine|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-10-02|language=en}}</ref>

== Business Model ==

2U  does not confer or offer any degrees.<ref>{{cite web|title=What's Ahead for 2U?|url=http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/31/what-is-ahead-of-2us-ipo.aspx|website=fool.com|publisher=Motley Fool|accessdate=2014-11-19}}</ref>   It provides its university partners with cloud-based software-as-a-service solutions to create online degree programs that feature live video classes, as well as an e learning platform that allows for close interaction between students and professors. The approach also includes a focus on student outcomes with small class sizes, career services, and field placements. This approach has led to a student retention rate of 84 percent.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lapowsky|first1=Issie|title=The Future of Online Education Is on Campus|url=http://www.inc.com/welcome.html?destination=http://www.inc.com/issie-lapowsky/future-online-education-on-campus.html|website=Inc.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> Students pay standard tuition, but instead of going to class once a week, they meet in a live video chat room with the professor and the other students.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Burke|first1=Adrienne|title=$97,500 for an Online Degree? 2U Is Worth It, Say Students|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/techonomy/2012/11/05/97500-for-an-online-degree-2u-is-worth-it-say-students/|website=Forbes.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>
2U signs long-term contracts, averaging between 10–15 years in length, with each of its partner universities. Contracts include a revenue sharing agreement between 2U and the school.<ref>{{cite web|title=IPO Preview: 2U|url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/2114083-ipo-preview-2u|website=Seeking Alpha|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>
Course content is also enhanced for mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Greenberg|first1=Molly|title=2U Releases Mobile Apps, Making it Easier For Students to Access Online Course Content|url=http://inthecapital.streetwise.co/2014/03/18/dc-tech-2u-releases-6-new-mobile-apps/|website=Inthecapital.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>

2U's "Semester Online" consortium of undergraduate universities included: [[Boston College]], [[Brandeis University]], [[Emory University]], [[Northwestern University|Northwestern]], [[University of Melbourne|The University of Melbourne]], [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College of Dublin]], [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], [[University of Notre Dame]], [[Wake Forest University]], and [[Washington University in St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Universities|url=http://2u.com/partners/|publisher=2U, Inc.|accessdate=24 September 2013}}</ref> The consortium was initially marketed as a platform for top-tier universities to offer online courses to paying students at participating universities.  The company announced in April 2014 that Semester Online would end in the summer of 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Straumsheim|first1=Carl|title=2U Ends Semester Online|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/04/03/online-education-provider-2u-disband-semester-online-consortium|publisher=Inside Higher Ed|date=3 April 2014}}</ref>

