{{nihongo|'''Dan Kogai'''|小飼弾|''Kogai Dan'', 1969 - }} is a Japanese open-source developer and alpha blogger, known for his blog ''404 Blog Not Found'' (ranked #5 in Japan<ref>[http://asiajin.com/blog/2008/08/18/japans-top-50-blogs/ "Japan's Top 50 Blogs"], ''Asiajin'', August 18, 2008.</ref>). He is also the former CTO of [[Livedoor]].<ref>[http://conferences.oreillynet.com/cs/os2005/view/e_spkr/2181 Profile of Dan Kogai], ''O'Reilly Open Source Convention'', 2005</ref>

== Background ==

Kogai went to middle school, but he had problems with formal education and skipped classes.<ref>[http://blog.livedoor.jp/dankogai/archives/51047973.html Kamihitoe], May 10th, 2008 (in Japanese).</ref> Immediately after he graduated from middle school at the age of 16 he passed the high-school equivalence exam, and up until age 18 he spent his time teaching senior students as a tutor and cram school teacher.<ref>[http://blog.livedoor.jp/dankogai/archives/50670613.html Daigaku ikitakattara gakkō ikanyaka ii no ni] Oct. 27, 2006 (in Japanese).</ref> He then entered the [[University of California, Berkeley]].

During his fourth year at university, his family's home burnt down, and he left school.<ref name="FAQ">[http://blog.livedoor.jp/dankogai/archives/22280762.html Kogai, Dan - Errata, Addeda & FAQ] May 17, 2005 (in Japanese).</ref> He made a living with the computer skills he had learnt at university, and at age 29 was headhunted by [[Takafumi Horie]] to join [[Livedoor#History|Livin' On the Edge]] (now [[Livedoor]]).<ref name="FAQ"/>

