{{Infobox video game | title = Zurk's Learning Safari | developer = [[Soleil Software]] | publisher = Soleil Software | image = Zurks learning safari 2784.jpg | caption = Win/Mac Cover art | platforms = DOS, Windows 3.x, Macintosh | release = 1993 | genre = Educational | modes = [[Single-player]] }} '''''Zurk's Learning Safari''''' is an educational adventure game by Soleil Software. It was followed by '''''Zurk's Rainforest Lab''''' and '''''Zurk's Alaskan Trek'''''. They were part of a larger ''Soleil's Whole World Learning Series''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejournal.com/articles/1996/09/01/part-of-soleils-whole-world-learning-series.aspx|title=Part of Soleil's Whole World Learning Series -- THE Journal|website=THE Journal|language=en|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>
==Production== In 1992, Barbara Christiani left Addison Wesley and founded educational software company Soleil Software with Ragni Pasturel. The studio's work included the Zurk series, and [[WorldWalker: Destination Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/obituaries/memorials/barbara-christiani?o=5185|title=Palo Alto Online - Lasting Memories - Barbara Christiani's memorial|website=www.paloaltoonline.com}}</ref> The game contains voice over work in English, French, and Spanish.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=eMKimy4DFaEC&pg=PA398&lpg=PA398&dq=Zurk's+Learning+Safari&source=bl&ots=ielmMGErzb&sig=DVARUhFwXDYF_WhC6Vqr1jnWXho&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj7jbXxvePaAhUCNrwKHQdUCEU4ChDoAQgtMAE#v=onepage&q=Zurk's+Learning+Safari&f=false|title=PC Mag|first=Ziff Davis|last=Inc|date=28 March 1995|publisher=Ziff Davis, Inc.|via=Google Books}}</ref> The game includes activities applicable to life sciences, reading and early math skills.<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/12/13/computers/8771dcb5-068b-44e1-bb25-f2382731c62a/|title=COMPUTERS|first=Don|last=Oldenburg|date=13 December 1993|publisher=|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>
==Reception== ===Critical reception=== PC Mag thought the game was "visually breaktaking", praising its sotrybook atmosphere.<ref name="auto"/> The Washington Post deemed it a "top-notch product".<ref name="auto1"/> The New York Times felt it was a " a very nice program" from an adult's perspective.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/01/science/personal-computers-3-child-size-safaris-in-animal-territory.html|title=PERSONAL COMPUTERS; 3 Child-Size Safaris In Animal Territory|first=Joshua|last=Mills|publisher=}}</ref> EdWeek praised ''Alaskan Trek'' for stimulating critical thinking.<ref name="secure.edweek.org">{{Cite web|url=http://secure.edweek.org/tm/articles/1998/01/01/04ohio.h09.html|title=Software Savvy - Education Week Teacher|website=secure.edweek.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref> The Palm Beach Post felt the gane;s best features allowed young players to create their own nature animations on the screen and assemble electronic notebooks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/134599366/|title=The Palm Beach Post from West Palm Beach, Florida on December 4, 1995 · Page 86|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en}}</ref>
===Awards and niminations=== * 1997 Only the Best honor from the Association for Supervision and Curriculum Development for ''Zurk's Alaskan Trek''.<ref name="secure.edweek.org"/>
